  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Yun Cheonggyeong
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I have long heard it said that those possessed of virtue inevitably speak with eloquence. For virtue's finest essence, when expressed outwardly, becomes speech—thus by listening to a person's words, one may truly know their character. How much more so with poetry and prose, which are the very quintessence of language itself. In this world, those who inherit family estates know well how to treasure rare jewels; they take pains to preserve even the blue felt of ancestral relics, passing them down through generations without loss. Yet how can we neglect to transmit the refined expression of our forebears' spiritual legacy?

    Master Yun Mungjdo labored earnestly in his studies and purified himself through ascetic discipline, becoming a learned scholar renowned throughout the age. Recognized by two successive courts, his virtue accumulated through disciplined living bore fruit in deeds of towering grandeur and in writings of luminous elegance—achievements upon which the realm itself depended, works that commanded universal admiration and were passed from lips to lips. Yet the Master himself paid them little mind, and left behind no organized manuscripts. His son, the Vice-Minister, grieved at the thought of these treasures being lost to the world. He labored for decades, gathering what survived through scattered memories and oral transmission, managing to recover but a handful of pieces. He set about arranging them into a collected work, yet fate intervened before his task was complete. Now Master Mok-song, inheriting his father's unfinished wish, has with his own hands compiled and arranged these works. He has also composed a biographical record, meticulously preserving the lineage and genealogical branches, placing all at the head of this collection of remaining writings. Thus the refined essence of the Master's virtue, expressed in his life's work, shall now flow down through the ages eternal. Those in ages to come who wish to glimpse the depths of the Master's accumulated virtue shall find here the evidence they seek—and so the true intention of the Vice-Minister is finally fulfilled. Surely this is what it means to inherit one's family legacy while understanding what truly merits preservation.

    I, Shin Suk-ju, born into a family of long standing, have studied under the Master since childhood and became his son-in-law, receiving from him an extraordinary measure of instruction and guidance. Through this connection I have come to understand something of his teachings, which have sustained me to this day. Now, as I see these collected works, newly completed and destined to endure forever, I am moved by a surge of emotion that cannot be contained.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: '청전(靑氈): Literally ''blue felt,'' a reference to ancestral treasures or family heirlooms passed down through generations.'
  - key: ''
    value: '문도공(文度公): An honorific title; Yun Mungjdo was a prominent Neo-Confucian scholar who served during two different court periods.'
  - key: ''
    value: '부정공(副正公): The Master''s son who held an official position (Vice-Minister); his efforts to preserve his father''s works were interrupted by his death.'
  - key: ''
    value: '무송공(茂松公): The grandson who completed the compilation of the collected works.'
